---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { data, formatNumber, formatPercent } from "../../lib/site-data";

const baseline = data.compare.regimes.find((regime) => regime.regime === "baseline") ?? data.compare.regimes[0];
const broad = data.compare.regimes.find((regime) => regime.regime === "broad");
const conservative = data.compare.regimes.find((regime) => regime.regime === "conservative");
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Method | FrontierGraph"
  description="How FrontierGraph builds a concept graph of economics and ranks underexplored links."
>
  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <span class="eyebrow">Method</span>
      <h1>How FrontierGraph turns the literature into a ranked concept graph.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        FrontierGraph is built around a simple division of labor: AI extracts graph structure from paper text, then a
        deterministic pipeline builds concept regimes, ranks missing links, and applies duplicate cleanup before the
        public recommendation surface is shown.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="card-grid method-top-grid">
        <article class="card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Corpus</span>
          <h3>{formatNumber(data.metrics.papers)} papers</h3>
          <p class="card-copy">
            Published economics-relevant papers selected through the current source regime, then filtered to the extraction-ready subset.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Extraction</span>
          <h3>{formatNumber(data.metrics.node_instances)} node instances</h3>
          <p class="card-copy">
            Title/abstract extraction yields paper-local nodes and edges with direction, evidence-method, and claim metadata.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="eyebrow">Default view</span>
          <h3>{data.default_view.regime} {data.default_view.mapping}</h3>
          <p class="card-copy">
            The public default keeps the ontology compact while still reaching exploratory coverage comparable to the other regimes.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section method-stack">
      <details class="method-detail" open>
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Corpus</span>
            <strong>What enters the graph</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The current public build uses the `FWCI core150 + adjacent150` source cut and the merged extraction corpus:
            {` `}<strong>{formatNumber(data.metrics.papers)}</strong> papers,
            {` `}<strong>{formatNumber(data.metrics.node_instances)}</strong> extracted node instances, and
            {` `}<strong>{formatNumber(data.metrics.edges)}</strong> extracted edges.
          </p>
          <p>
            The site defaults to the concept graph rather than the older JEL browse layer. JEL remains a coarse fallback, not the core ontology.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Graph extraction</span>
            <strong>What the model does</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The model extracts paper-local nodes and edges from titles and abstracts only. Nodes carry local study context
            where available, while edges carry relation directionality, causal presentation, edge role, claim status,
            evidence method, and supporting text.
          </p>
          <p>
            AI stops at graph extraction. Ranking, ontology comparison, and duplicate cleanup are deterministic and inspectable.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Ontology</span>
            <strong>How paper-local labels become reusable concepts</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            FrontierGraph compares three support-gated ontology regimes. The public default is
            {` `}<strong>{baseline.label} exploratory</strong>, with
            {` `}<strong>{formatNumber(baseline.head_count)}</strong> head concepts and
            {` `}<strong>{formatPercent(baseline.soft_coverage)}</strong> exploratory coverage.
          </p>
          <div class="pill-row">
            {broad && <span class="field-pill">Broad: {formatNumber(broad.head_count)} heads</span>}
            <span class="field-pill">Baseline: {formatNumber(baseline.head_count)} heads</span>
            {conservative && <span class="field-pill">Conservative: {formatNumber(conservative.head_count)} heads</span>}
          </div>
          <p>
            “Strict” mappings keep only high-confidence concept identity. “Exploratory” mappings include the strict map plus
            nearest-head assignments for broader product-facing coverage.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Ranking</span>
            <strong>How missing links are scored</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The ranker combines deterministic graph signals such as path support, gap bonus, motif completion, mediator
            structure, co-occurrence scarcity, and hub penalties. The goal is to surface concept pairs that look
            structurally underconnected relative to the surrounding literature graph.
          </p>
          <p>
            The public opportunities page and app both use the same suppressed baseline exploratory top slice rather than a separate marketing list.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Duplicate suppression</span>
            <strong>How near-synonym loops are cleaned up</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Ontology alone does not prevent recommendation loops such as concept variants ranking against one another. A
            deterministic suppression layer therefore removes or down-ranks same-family duplicate pairs on the public
            baseline surface.
          </p>
          <div class="pill-row">
            <span class="field-pill">{formatNumber(data.metrics.suppressed_candidate_count)} visible candidates</span>
            <span class="field-pill">{formatNumber(data.metrics.duplicate_loops_removed_top100)} duplicate loops removed in top 100</span>
          </div>
          <p>
            The app keeps base score and adjusted score visible so the cleanup layer remains auditable.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Regime comparison</span>
            <strong>Why sensitivity is exposed rather than hidden</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>{data.compare.default_reason}</p>
          <p>{data.compare.strict_reason}</p>
          <p>
            The website and app treat ontology choice as an inspectable modeling decision. Baseline exploratory is the
            default product view, but the other regimes remain available as advanced comparison surfaces.
          </p>
          <div class="button-row">
            <a class="button-secondary" href="/compare/">Open comparison page</a>
            <a class="button-tertiary" href="/downloads/">Download summaries</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
